        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>1) Imaging: During ALMA cycle 2, the diameter of Saturn will vary between 18.5"
and 15.2", hence larger than the maximum recoverable scale (MRS) with the ACA
at 345 GHz, i.e. 12.1". However, the size of the disk of Saturn will be exactly
known at the time of the observations, and the continuum temperature will be
measured concomitantly by Cassini/CIRS. Hence, a deconvolution process will
allow us to retrieve a MRS up to 1.5 times the standard MRS, based on our
experience from Cycle 0 Venus ALMA observations. The configuration suited for
our required angular resolution of 0.6" is configuration C34-2. There is no
problem of uv coverage for our proposal.

2) Sensitivity: Our required sensitivity is 15 mJy/beam at 345 GHz per 30-kHz
channel in order to achieve a rms of 12 m/s ont the position of the doppler
shifted CO line at the western and eastern limbs. This estimation is based on
detection of the CO 3-2 line on Saturn using the JCMT.

3) Correlator setup: Our main goal is the measurement of the winds with a small
rms. Hence, we selected a resolution of 26 m/s (no binning) over a bandwith of
51 km/s. This bandwidth is larger than the line width (2 km/s) and larger than
the planet rotation of 20 km/s. We added a broad continuum baseband centered
on the CO line to obtain an excellent measurement of the Saturn's continuum in
order to retrieve the position of the limb very accurately. In the LSB, we
selected a CH3OH line. CH3OH is not yet detected in Saturn, but is expected due
to the presence of methane and water in the stratosphere.

4) Calibration: we will use the system-defined calibration.

5) Bandpass accuracy: a 15 mJy/beam sensitivity over a continuum of 1.7 Jy/beam
at the limb requires a RF of 0.1%.

6) Scheduling/Time constraints: There is no time constraint for these
observations.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
