    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>In Saturn, winds have been measured by tracking cloud motions. In the cloudless
stratosphere, 200 km above the cloud level, the winds have never been measured
but only indirectly infer from the measured thermal structure, the so-called
thermal winds. This situation is not satisfaying and hampers our understanding
of Saturn's stratospheric dynamics. Indeed, the thermal winds determination is
affected by several uncertainties, and does not apply at the equator, where
the largest wind speed is expected. Moreover, the difference between the real
wind speed and the thermal wind speed is a major parameter to quantify the
main driving forces of Saturn's stratospheric dynamics, i.e. atmospheric waves.
Hence, only a direct measurement of Saturn's stratospheric wind will enable
a consistent undertanding and modelisation of Saturn's dynamics above the cloud
level. Our ALMA measurement will compliment and capitalize on concomitant
observations by the Cassini spacecraft. The ALMA measurement will be use to
constrain a General Circulation Model of Saturn, which will serve as a benchmark
to model General circulation in Solar System and extrasolar Giant Gaseous
Planets.</prp:abstract>
